      <p>You don't need to spend $150 or more to get a capable wet/dry shop vac for your job site. Some of the best-rated contractor vacuums on Amazon cost well under $80 — and they still deliver strong suction, solid build quality, and the versatility to handle both wet and dry debris.</p>
      <p>The key is knowing which budget shop vacs actually hold up on a real construction site. We've sorted through the ratings, real-world contractor reviews, and specs to find the affordable wet/dry vacs that offer the best value without cutting corners on performance.</p>

      <h2>What to Look for in a Budget Shop Vac</h2>
      <p>When you're shopping under $80, you have to prioritize what matters. Here's what to focus on:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tank size matters most at this price point.</strong> You'll find 6–10 gallon models under $80. A 6-gallon tank is fine for an individual contractor, but if you're doing demo or heavy cleanup, stretch for a 10-gallon model.</li>
        <li><strong>Peak HP is less important than filter quality.</strong> A $60 vac with 4 HP and a good cartridge filter will outperform a $60 vac with 5 HP and a cheap filter — because the filter clogs fast and kills suction.</li>
        <li><strong>Look for included accessories.</strong> Budget vacs sometimes skip the hose, crevice tool, or wet nozzle. Check the product listing to make sure you're getting a complete kit.</li>
        <li><strong>Poly tanks are your friend.</strong> At this price, polypropylene tanks are lighter and won't rust. Metal tanks in the budget range are thin and prone to denting.</li>
        <li><strong>Wet/dry capability is standard.</strong> Every vac on this list handles both, but check that a foam filter sleeve is included for wet pickup — you don't want to destroy your cartridge filter on the first spill.</li>
      </ul>

