      <h2>Should You Buy a Budget Shop Vac or Save for a Premium Model?</h2>
      <p>This is the real question for every contractor. Here's an honest breakdown:</p>
      <p><strong>Buy a budget vac if:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>You're an individual contractor who needs a vac for light to medium cleanup</li>
        <li>You need a second vac to keep in the truck or at a specific job site</li>
        <li>You're just starting out and need to equip your van on a tight budget</li>
        <li>Your work doesn't involve heavy fine-dust production (drywall, concrete cutting)</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Consider spending more if:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>You're doing heavy demo or renovation work that fills a tank quickly</li>
        <li>You need HEPA filtration for OSHA silica dust compliance</li>
        <li>You use the vac for dust extraction on power tools all day long</li>
        <li>Noise level is critical (budget vacs run at standard 85–90 dB)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips to Get the Most Out of a Budget Shop Vac</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Buy a spare cartridge filter immediately.</strong> The #1 reason budget vacs lose suction is a clogged filter. Having a spare means you swap in seconds instead of stopping to clean.</li>
        <li><strong>Use dust bags for dry debris.</strong> A simple paper dust bag extends filter life by 3–5x. They're cheap ($5–$8 per pack) and make disposal much cleaner.</li>
        <li><strong>Don't overload the tank.</strong> Budget vacs have smaller tanks. Empty at 75% full — letting it fill completely reduces airflow and strains the motor.</li>
        <li><strong>Keep the foam filter handy for wet pickup.</strong> Never use a paper cartridge filter for liquids. The foam sleeve is washable and reusable. Always dry it before storing.</li>
        <li><strong>Store the vac indoors or covered.</strong> Budget poly tanks can become brittle after extended UV exposure. Keep it in the van or under a tarp.</li>
      </ul>

